    "So here's the deal with strongholds. First and foremost, the current idea for strongholds stemmed from the old siege weapons. While wonderful, they truly didn't have an impact on the game world or any fight in which they were used."

    Incorrect.

    The current idea for strongholds, what little I know about it, seems to have been taken directly from the previous idea of Strongholds, the lovingly titled Ithilien Domination mode I and other admins worked on. These did have a very visible impact on the gameworld: inept Gondor handling led the Siege of Osgiliath to happen earlier, and a lot more viciously, than may have occured if they didn't get their ass kicked. Players worked for weeks in advanced, Morgul completely turned itself on its head in order to become siege-efficient, Gondor struggled valiantly. There were a few 20 vs 20 almost-entirely PvP fights. Players made a difference.

    "The Fall of Osgiliath was [SPOILER ALERT] scripted. -Nothing- the players did affected it's outcome at all."

    Incorrect - to a point.

    The Fall was scripted, but it was scripted like a Choose Your Own Adventure - players could decide to do certain things, which would influence how things ended up later. During the Fall, there were a number of goals, checkpoints, milestones etc. that if the players did them, certain events would happen, or would happen sooner, or later, or not happen at all. Of course, the problem with a one-off event, is you never get to see the way things may have turned out if you did them another way. But, players can rest secure knowing that they may have done things differently, and it may have had different effects.

    "Blah blah blah... code is hard... people quit..."

    I threw mini-forts together in a week. I threw the original Stronghold system together in a couple of months. For both of those, I didn't use mprogs, didn't use oprogs, used a very old system of r-progs, and a very old set of crafts. No mobile cues either.

    If I could build not one, but two location-based assault systems that encourage strategic gameplay, without any of the above, then you can do it using code.
